<seg id=1> Guangxi Uses 150 Million U.S. Dollars In Foreign Investment To Build Basic Infrastructure For Water Transport </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> XINHUA NEWS AGENCY WIRE Nanning, March 14 (Lu Hankui reporting): According to information put out by the Zhuangzu Autonomous Region Transportation Bureau in Guangxi, the province has used payments from the World Bank, the Bank of Asia, and Holland and Korea, among other countries, totaling from 150 million U.S. dollars so far, to build basic infrastructure for a waterways transportation system. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> In the last few years, Guangxi has seen increasing development of itself a conduit to the ocean for the southwestern region of China. </seg>
<seg id=4> Openness to the outside world along with greater efforts to attract foreign investment are being used to solve the problem of insufficient funds. </seg>
<seg id=5> The Xijiang shipping hub, with a total investment of more than 2 billion Renminbi yuan, is in its second stage of construction. It has used payments of 80 million U.S. dollars from the World Bank. At present 80 percent of the main construction has been completed, with 50 percent of the concrete pouring finished. </seg>
<seg id=6> The city of Fangchenggang is in the second stage of construction (including the highway to Qinzhou City), using 52 million U.S. dollars from the Asia Development Bank. The highway is scheduled to be finished and ready for use by the second half of this year. </seg>
<seg id=7> The complementary infrastructure project at Beihai Harbor is using 10 million U.S. dollars in funds from the Korean government, </seg>
<seg id=8> while the complementary infrastructure project at Qinzhou Harbor is using 13 million U.S. dollars in funds from the Dutch government. </seg>
<seg id=9> These construction projects are all proceeding smoothly. </seg>
</p>
